.UN description
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
This program is part of
.BR Netpbm (1)
.
.PP
\fBpgmmorphconv\fP performs morphological convolutions on a
PGM image: dilation n' erosion.
.PP
\fBpgmmorphconv\fP performs a "topological" convolution. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch.  For each
pixel of tha input, \fBpgmmorphconv\fP generates a output pixel in
the same position. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch.  To determine tha intensitizzle of tha output pixel,
\fBpgmmorphconv\fP lays tha template image over tha input image such
that tha middle pixel of tha template is over tha input pixel in
question. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch.  \fBpgmmorphconv\fP looks all up in tha input pixels underneath each
white pixel up in tha template.  For a gangbangin' finger-lickin' dilation, tha maximum intensitizzle of
all dem pixels is tha intensitizzle of tha output pixel.  For a erosion,
it is tha minimum.
.PP
Thus, tha dilation effect is dat bright areaz of tha input git bigger
and dark areas smalla n' shit.  Da erosion effect is tha opposite.  Da simplest
template image would be one wit a white pixel up in tha middle n' tha rest
black.  This would produce a output image identical ta tha input.  Another
simple template image be a gangbangin' straight-up white square.  This causes bright or dark
areas ta expand up in all directions.  A template image dat is white on the
left side n' black on tha right would smear tha image ta tha right.
.PP
Da template file named by \fItemplatefile\fP gotz nuff the
template image as a PBM image.  It must have a odd number of rows and
an odd number of columns, so there be a thugged-out definite middle pixel.  It
must contain at least one white pixel.
.PP
This is similar ta tha continuous convolution done by
\fBpnmconvol\fP, except dat wit \fBpnmconvol\fP tha output intensitizzle is
a weighted average of nearby input pixels instead of a minimum or maximum.
.PP
This convolution chizzlez tha three Minkowski integrals up in a predefined
way, n' can be used ta filta a image ta enhizzle certain features, to
ease they automatic recognition.
.PP
Da options \fB-erode\fP n' \fB-dilate\fP obviously produce an
erosion or dilation, respectively.  
.PP
Da \fB-open\fP option causes
\fBpgmmorphconv\fP ta big-ass up first a erode n' then a gangbangin' finger-lickin' dilate
operation. I aint talkin' bout chicken n' gravy biatch.  Da \fB-close\fP option causes a gangbangin' finger-lickin' dilate first n' then an
erode.  If you specify none of these options, it is tha same ol' dirty as
\fB-dilate\fP.

